President Uhuru Kenyatta is today scheduled to address the world&rsquo;s most powerful leaders, the G7 Summit in Taormina, Sicily, Italy.The G7 leaders are US President Donald Trump, Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, French President Emmanuel Macron, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Italian Prime Minister Paolo Gentiloni, Japanese Prime Minister Shinz&#333; Abe and UK&rsquo;s PM Theresa May.Italy currently holds the rotating G7 Presidency and the theme of this year&rsquo;s summit is &lsquo;Building the foundations of Renewed Trust&rsquo;.Kenya, Ethiopia, Tunisia and Nigeria have been invited to represent the interests of the continent.State House spokesman Manoah Esipisu yesterday said the President will use this high-profile event to showcase Kenya&rsquo;s achievements.&ldquo;G7 leaders will be in Italy to make decisions that impact on global security, the confrontation with terrorism and the continuity of the global economic order. We want to demonstrate that Kenya is worthy to be the leading partner to that club, that our prosperity and security directly feeds into their agenda,&rdquo; he said.&ldquo;President Kenyatta has been invited to speak specifically on the timeliness and challenges brought about by innovation as a factor of economic growth and development in Africa. This is a massive recognition of the strides that Kenya is making and has made in the innovation and tech area for which we are now a recognised leader on our continent.&rdquo;Industrialisation CS Adan Mohammed said Kenya has made remarkable strides in creating an enabling environment that is conducive to do business.&ldquo;We have made major strides in making Kenya a model in Africa. For two consecutive years, we have been ranked by the World Bank as the second most improved country globally on doing business rankings, rising a cumulative 44 places in two years and rising to the topmost reformed country in Africa in 2017,&rdquo; he said.National Counter Terrorism Centre director Martin Kimani and political commentator Andrew Ndolo said the meeting will not only boost Kenya&rsquo;s image internationally, but will also help build partnerships that will strengthen economic opportunities and security.&ldquo;As a democracy with a growing and mixed economy, that is facing global terrorism, Kenya&rsquo;s success is key to the G-7&rsquo;s democratic countries, whose priorities are protecting global security, protecting democracy and expanding opportunities for their private sector,&rdquo; Kimani said.&ldquo;President Kenyatta&rsquo;s presence will bring sharp focus to that and lead to increased investment and engagement with Kenya.&rdquo;Ndolo said the invitation is a recognition by the G7 of the important position Kenya occupies in the continent and a clear endorsement of the President&rsquo;s leadership, two years after he was cleared of crimes against humanity charges at the ICC.